Friday, January 1, 1965

A rather bad night last night. Little sleep.
Watched the Rose Parade with the kid's
and the Sugar and Rose Bowl games, also at night the Orange Bowl.

Saturday, January 2, 1965

Worked for a while today on change in the keys and tables required by Bogert's recent specimens.
Watched the Gator Bowl game at Jacksonville, Fla, between Oklahoma and Florida state; also the shrine east and west game at San Francisco played in a mud puddle.

Sunday, January 3, 1965

got up this morning at 4:15 and cleaned up a lot of desk work.
Went up to the Millers to say goodbye to Harry and Gracie.
Watched the St. Louis-green Bay game for awhile.
Worked on salvini, oaxacus, and gloydi in the keys and tables. Made some real progress.

Wednesday, January 6, 1965

At the office this morning.
Brief conference with Sinnott and PMK
Worked on revision of chapter 1, status and really got my teeth into it. Made some very encouraging progress; have boiled it down to a few things that must be looked up or checked.
Continued work on chapter 1 in the afternoon and late evening.
In the early evening went to an illustrated program by Charlie Schroeder on Kenya, New Zealand, Tasmania, Sydney, and New Guinea.

Friday, January 8, 1965

At the office early this morning.
Then to a meeting of the hillary commission until nearly noon.
Went to funeral of Jessie Smith (Mrs Lawrence) at La Jolla in the early afternoon.
Went to Zoo and met Ray Folsom the snake dealer. He had a good young specimen of Crotalus durissus culminatus that was brought down for photographing which will check off another item in the identification series.
Jay and Mary Ann came to dinner tonight and watched TV until fairly late.

Saturday, January 9, 1965

Spent the morning on miscellaneous
catching up, letters, and getting ready
for my talk this noon.
At noon went to he gas co
management conference at Vacation
Village. Gave my talk entitled
"Lessons from the Past". It seemed to
go ok. By holding the slips up
there was good lightening) I could
see to read them ok, but I definitely
can't read as fluently as I once could.
I think I will have to read more
slowly to make a talk more effective.
Joe Coop came in at 3:30. He wanted
a British Herp. Journal. Also took his
Santa Barbara helleri with him.
Allan came in at 4 and we
talked KW affairs until 5:30.
Watched TV tonight.

Spent a lot of time today working
on a defective electric fixture in the
dinning room.

now have once one loose end to pick up.

Page Edit History:
  • JanessaS 03/07/2013 11:31 PM

Monday, January 11, 1965

A pretty tough day today. Went up to Dr. Howe's office at 9 AM and stayed until 11:20. Nothing to eat or drink since 6:30 last night. Had a number of x-rays and a cystoscopic check up; the latter quite unpleasant with painful after effects.

Then down to the office until noon. Came home, had lunch, felt punk. GG put one of her denture plates down the toilet this morning. Had a plumber come up and check sewer traps -- no luck.

In the afternoon had a meeting of the Library Committee of the Natural History Museum from 3:30 to 4:00; then a meeting of the Directors from 4:00 to 5:20. This went ok I think in view of the fact that I presided and felt shaky.

Pauline Des Granges called up tonight; water pipe broken at Museum.

Tuesday, January 12, 1965

At the office this morning.
Did carding; also worked on Gulf of California list.

Spent part of the afternoon checking Cristmas Cards.

Went to do dinner tonight with Oscar Cotton and John at the Convention Hall; then to the grand opening of the new Civic Theatre and the San Diego Symphony. Certainly a magnificent opera house for a town of San Diego's size.

Page Edit History:
  • HerpVolunteer 05/13/2014 03:55 PM

Wednesday, January 13, 1965

At the office this morning.
Did some carding and other misc work. Finished checking Xmas Cards.

At 12:45 went over to the Zoo and took part in another Zooname episode. As usual there was plenty of lost time but I did get home by 2:30. Was extremely tired.

Went to performance of "who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf" at the new Civic Theatre tonight. A good performance of a lousy play -- very rough language. As for the plot, I couldn't understand it.

Page Edit History:
  • HerpVolunteer 05/13/2014 03:56 PM
  • Szlyna 11/27/2013 12:07 AM

Thursday, January 14, 1965

Quite active this morning. First went to Bohemian Bakery for stuff to send to kids. Ordered on the phone last night.

The to the office. Carding, income tax, finished island table for Chapter 2, worked again on Chapter 1, now virtually finished.

Had a phone call from Oregon from someone who wishes to process and sell venom.

At 2PM Chernoff and I met Cobb of Stanford Research for a long discussion of the San Pasqual project and their report thereon.

Then went to the Natural History and talked over new Director problem with Baylov Brooke.

Friday, January 15, 1965

At the office this morning. Gave a cocktail party and standup feed at home tonight 5:30 to 9:30. About 35 present.

Page Edit History:
  • Szlyna 11/27/2013 12:11 AM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:15 PM

Saturday, January 16, 1965

Miscellaneous filing and other clean-up work this morning. Then started on C. Catalinensis, assembling the data on the new specimens lately received from Sloan. Made progress.

Went out to call on Laurence Smith, whose wife recently died at La Jolla. This took from 10:30 until 1:00.

This afternoon Susan de Treville came in to talk about the surgical removal of venom glands. She had a big ruber whose venom glands had recently been removed by a veterinarian. She said it ate well and it seemed healthy. She handled it freely; it was quite tame. She wants to do future experimental with the removal of venom glands. I promised to give her any references I might have. Unfortunately I was dressing to go out and couldn't spare her any time.

This evening went to a concert of the LA Philharmonic at the new Civic Theatre. Guests of the Jess Haright's at a pre-concert dinner at the Grant Hotel.

Sunday, January 17, 1965

A little miscellaneous work this morning. Finished catalinensis as far as I could go.

Then started Income Tax calculations, making the preliminary statistical compilation from my cash book.

Hunted for Tart correspondence in the evening. Found some.

Tuesday, January 19, 1965

At the office this morning.
Wrote letters.
Worked on Income Tax
Conference with Phil.

Appointment with Dr. Howe at 3:30.
Continue to take medicine for 3 more days; 1 pill before meals with one glass of water.
See him in 3 months.
If I have another cystitis attack, start taking pills but let him know.
All he did today was make another retention test.

Tonight went to a Rotary meeting at the Cuyamaca Club given by 20 Past Presidents honoring Dr. Geo Huff for his acceptance of the District Governorship.

Saturday, January 23, 1965

Worked this morning on replacement of last letter to Encyclopedia Britannica re Rattlesnake article. Then filing etc. Then back to annual financial report.
Finished it as far as I can go now.

Worked on catalinensis this afternoon. Find it has a far atrox characters but most of them.

Tuesday, January 26, 1965

At the office this morning. Made up an order for stamps from the Philatelic Agency and got the necessary cashier's check.

Worked on the proper name for the northern copperhead. Agkistrodon Contortrix Mokason . Finished this item.

Tonight went to the San Diego Symphony Concert. Robert Gerle was the soloist, playing Mendelssohn's Violin Concerto.

After the concert went to the Art Johnson's for a party for Gerle. A very pleasurable affair, but I was very tired when we got home at midnight.

Wednesday, January 27, 1965

Finished the corrections for Chapter 1. Now all that remains is to prepare a copy to serve as the manuscript; about interlineation. Will be written in red ink; longer tome to be type written on yellow Ins. paper.
Today received from the press two xerox copies up to the end of Chapter 1. This has been long delayed.

Meeting of Zoo Finance Committee and Trustees from 6 to 9:15 PM.

Was advised that Sherman Platt is working on the revision of the U.C. contract covering the second edition of Rattlesnakes.

Thursday, January 28, 1965

Meeting of the citizen's Advisory Committee on Air Pollution (of which I am chairman) this morning from 9:30 to 11:50. A very interesting meeting with new developments in auto control devises explained by Jiro Maga and Don Jensen.

Then went to the office for a few minutes.

Watched the Churchill funeral on TV this morning.

Shaw came around this afternoon and selected whatever herpetological papers he wanted out of my surplus. Dinner at home tonight for about 24 people, including the PMK's and the DMM's. The Eglers were here -- gravy guild's future inlaws; and the Snells, Joffery Conyers new inlaws, both from Newport Beach.

Friday, February 5, 1965

At the office this morning. Made a copy (Xerox) of Chapter 1 to send to Mollath for comments. Worked on accounts in the afternoon.

This evening went to a Van Cliburn concert, followed by a supper party at the Cuyamaca Club given by Harry Callaway. Fine, rich Mexican food.

Saturday, February 6, 1965

Put aside Rattlesnakes this morning and began work in Federal Income Tax return. It will be complicated this year by extensive changes in the form. Made fair progress.

Went to the Charity Ball at Coronado Hotel tonight. Started at 5:40; home at 12:20. Went with Oscar Cotton, Clara Torrance (who took us to dinner) Fanny Sherman, Violet Holloway + GG. The milton Hellers joined us at dinner. We first went to the Wholford cocktail party. Good food then to the dinner. More good food. The show in the ballroom was better than usual; all remembrances of past times. Very well done and easy to sit through. After that dancing with horrible loud music; very tiring to sit through.

Page Edit History:

Sunday, February 7, 1965

Worked on income tax today but made indifferent progress. Took a long time to gather data for a reply to Peter Brownrigg of Princeton who wishes to compare the fangs of a rattlesnake with the tusks of a sabre-tooth tiger. This was a time-coming chore.

Went to Philip's for a while this afternoon.

Concert of Los Angeles Philharmonic tonight. Guest conductor Paul Kletzki. A good concert.

Wednesday, February 10, 1965

A busy day spent with cousins the Jerome Kohlbergs of New Rodrelle, N.Y.

Picked up Leet at 11AM (at the office until 10:30) then to the Beach and Tennis Club where the Kohlbergs were staying. To Amy Jos, and to the Valencia Hotel for lunch. Back to Leets as they could see her house and stuff. Then home, picked up GG and took the bus ride at the Zoo. To Alice Heynerman's for cocktails, then to Chuck Wagon for dinner. Out to La Jolla to take visitors back to the Beach Club, then home at 10, pretty well worn out. They are pleasant, interesting people. Forgot to say we visited Allan's after the Zoo ride.

Friday, February 19, 1965

At the office this morning. Finished the first draft of income tax. All it needs is checking and copying. Went to see Dr. Howe at 10:45. Said I had a staph carbuncle. He opened it up; took out the core. Prescribed Polycillin. Said I had done the right thing to see him.

KW co directors 2 to 3; meeting of building site committee at the office 3:30 to 5:20.

Went to Scholia tonight. Judge Haines talked on the water situation in Florida. Allan attended his first meeting.

Sunday, February 21, 1965

Back bothering me today so that I can't sit up in comfort. Wrote a few letters.
Looked for important new references in Russell's new red bibliography. Finished Federal Income Tax forms. Ready to sign and send in.

Tuesday, February 23, 1965

At the office this morning. Conference with Phil.
4 Canadians came in for a visit this afternoon, Friends of Rev. Austin Mackie of Vernon, B.C.. They said he had passed away about a month ago. He had sent me much information on the hibernating habitats of C.V. Oreganus in British Columbia. The Canadians were James P. Burbruge of Box 355 Kelowna, B.C.; Mr. and Mrs. BM Baker of 364 Bernard Ave., Kelowna, B.C. and another woman whose name I didn't catch. We talked snakes from 4 to 5:30.

Went to San Diego Symphony Concert tonight; Malcolm Frager, pianist. Stumbled going upstairs this afternoon and banged my right chest on the newer post. Made a black-and-blue bruise.

Wednesday, March 17, 1965

At the office this morning. Had a discussion with Sinnot (at his initiation) of my future with the Company in crew of my impending resignation from the Board of Directors and Executive Committee. I will continue as a consultant with my present salary (less any addition to my pension, so there will be no net gain). I am invited to attend all meetings of the Directors and of the Executive Committee. Announcement will be made of my continuance as a consultant to stop the chatter about going away parties. So as far as money is concerned I will be out director's fees about 2.25 a month.

Talked over some distribution problems with Phil.

HH Watson, formerly construction supt, came in and I've had a long chat over old times. He lives in Minneapolis; retired at Northern States Power in 1955. Worked on Maslin's Colorado Distrus?? paper.

Got Standford Research Institute's report on San Pasqual this afternoon and read about half of it.

Saturday, April 24, 1965

This morning spent a lot of time and energy rearranging the data files containing the accumulation for the second edition of rattlesnakes. This was done to avoid a recurrence of what happened last week when I couldn't find the second copy of the manuscript of Chapter 2 and spent a lot of time hunting it. Maybe the new system will work -- I hope so but the fundamental difficulty is that I have lost my memory. This is proving a serious handicap for everything I do.

Got copies of the preface and Introduction ready to submit to Shaw.

Went to the Old-Timers Dinner Meeting tonight. There were 112 present. 55 had died since last year's meeting. Got home a little after 8.

Sunday, June 20, 1965

Today made a study of the number of specimens involved in the statistics in Table 2:7 to see which subspecies were desirable to authenticate the statistics. There are quite a few but I don't propose to do anything beyond being on the lookout for any easy to obtain. I certainly don't purpose to indulge in any extensive borrowing campaign at this late date.

Looked over Soule's two specimens of cerralvensis, which proves to be a very weak subspecies.

Went to two cocktail parties in Point Loma this afternoon: the Robt Thompsons and Wm T. Stephens'.

Friday, August 20, 1965

Got up specially early today to take GG down to the airfield where she departed for the East and Europe with Gracie and Janet. Everything went OK, although I had to park quite a distance away, which tired me somewhat. There was quite a crowd down to see them off.

Sunday, August 29, 1965

Worked on Zoogeography this morning and made progress especially with bibliography.

Watched football this noon.

Wrote GG in the early afternoon.

Took the letters down to the post office; then called for Alice Heyneman and Dorothy Colbentz and took them to dinner at the Chuck Wagon.

Dr. Findlay A. Russell called at 10 tonight. Said he was just back from Portal in the Churicahua Mts and that he had just had a report that Dr. Fred A. Shannon had been bitten by a rattler and was in a very serious condition. The accident had happened in the vicinity of Klondyke, Graham County, Arizona. This snake was said to be large and dark. What could it be. I checked the maps and told his atrox, scutulatus, molassus, or cerberus (checked this the following morning). All are found in or close to the Pinalino Mts. He said they had monovalent antivenins for all of these and might sent them over. He had not thought of cerberus. I told him the venom was probably like that of helleri or oreganus. He said Shannon was reported as comatose and vomiting blood.

Page Edit History:

Monday, August 30, 1965

Got up and worked this morning at 4:30 Checked maps of Arizona for what I told Russell last night. It seemed OK.

Went to the office at 9. Worked on letter to GG, then home for morning mail, then to PO to mail letter to GG at NY, by airmail special delivery.

Russell called this afternoon from LA. Shannon was very bad shape. Had stopped breathing They were flying him over to LA for treatment, if he lasted that long. At one time during a lucid moment he had told them he was bitten by a scutulatus.
_____________________________________________________
Aug. 31 continued

was doing assessment work on a mine that he owned near Klondyke and found the scute under a board. The snake was about 32" long and struck practically its full length hitting him on the index finger of his right hand. The got him to their car and he collapsed so they knew it was serious. They used 4 vials of antivenin at that time. Russell told me at length about what was done in treatment and transportation but I cannot recall the details. He was dead on arrival at the LA Hospital. He said he had treated 113 rattler bite cases and this was the first case lost. Shannon's wife is pregnant.

Feeling better this afternoon. I think the red pills are having some effect.

Tuesday, September 1 , 1965

Got up at 5 and made more slips for Brattstrom, 1964A, fig 41 map.

A mixed up day, without much accomplished.

Went to the office for awhile, then to the Zoo where I looked at Russell's big snake from Chiapas Mexico. It seems to have some likelesses to durissus, some to basiliscus. Will not know until it can be closely examined and the scales counted, if at all. It has a faint stripe on the neck and a decided vertebral ridge, but the ridge is also present in a large specimen from Colima.

From the Zoo, after borrowing a Bogert-Oliver Sonora report, I went home for the mail. Completed a letter to GG and took to the post office for mailing.

Sunday, September 19, 1965

Got up early this morning and gave the Population Explosion speech a final overhaul. The morning paper was late.

Today I gave the Population Explosion speech before the San Diego Surgical Society at Islandia. It was a noon breakfast. I did a perfectly terrible job. The speech was much too long , repetitions and tiring to the audience. The trouble was the rostrum was too low and I couldn't see to read. I could hold up the papers into the proper range but couldn't keep my wits about me to do it continuously. The result was that I stumbled through it with many interruptions, pauses and misstatements. It was really an awful performance. The people (surgeons and their wives) were polite, but they couldn't get out fast enough when it was over. It took 55 minutes. I will never do it again without cutting out the last 1/4. At one point I got dizzy and had to hang on to the podium for support. Fortunately this soon passed. I presume this was due to using glasses at the wrong distance.

Sunday, October 3, 1965

Finished with Bogerts two specimen's from Oaxaca, which are the only two specimens awaiting return to distant museums.

Friday, October 29, 1965

At the office most of the morning. Made a little progress with zoogeography.

Also went over to the Library and received a photostat (Xerox) from the National Library of Medicine

Wrote some letters in the afternoon.

This afternoon and evening I got the idea that the best way to eliminate the impasse that has so long slowed up the covering of the proposed addition of a section on zoogeography was to use all of he material I have painfully accumulated on the subject as an extension to the discussion of phylogeny and particularly the changes necessary in fig. 3:4. I hope this new direction of attack will break the barrier and that I will finally be able to complete Chapter 3 satisfactorily.

Page Edit History:

Saturday, October 30, 1965

This morning I got up early and started to rearrange and organize for the proposed new approach all the material that I have acculated for zoogeography. This involved a new system of filing data in a new series of envelopes.

At 9 AM I went down town and bought at Arey-Jones enough envelopes for the new system.

Returning home I prepared the new envelopes and a filing system for them.

This afternoon I went over the Ms of Chapter 3 to see what changes would be necessary because of the proposed revised treatment. I found it necessary to revise and somewhat expand the treatment of phylogeny, dropping zoogeography as a separate subject. This shouldn't be too difficult. I think all the data I have gathered will be useful. The whole matter has taken a more logical pattern. Much of what I have done will not be wasted; but if originally I had mapped my approach in line with that finally adopted, much time (and pain) would have been saved.

Monday, November 8, 1965

George Lindsay picked us up at 9AM and we caught the PSA at 10 for San Francisco without difficulty.

An uneventful trip, although interesting to me as it was my first air trip in many years. My last was a trip in a trimotored Ford from Fresno south way back (I think) in the 1920's. That time I was very sick. The present speedy jets are quite a different story.

George had a car at the San Francisco airport and took us to the Clift Hotel where a reservation had been made. We had lunch at the Clift Coffee Shop and, as usual, I ate too much.

Then I went out to the Academy via bus and met Alan J. Galloway, Chairman of the Board. Also met some of the librarians. They had done a fine job digging out many of the pamphlets and books I had listed in previous letters to George. They had even secured items from U.C. and Stanford, not contained in the CAS library. This saved me a lot of time. I worked until nearly 5, by which time I was quite pooped, so I returned to the hotel via bus. I didn't disturb George as I knew he would insist on returning me to the hotel.

Went to dinner with Dorie at a French joint on O'Farrell near Taylor. A fine day today and very productive.

Thursday, November 11, 1965

This morning GG and I went over to Berkley. She visited Amy's relative while I called on Conrad Mollath at the University Press. We, Mollath and Lloyd G. Lyman* of the Press discussed the Rattlesnake Book and the progress of the Second Edition from 10 to 1:30 including lunch at the Student Union I acquainted them with the slowness of progress I was making because of my age and that I was fearful that if I couldn't finish it (the Ms) nobody could pick it up. We went into many details of what should be done and had a most interesting discussion. It was finally agreed that Mollath would write me as to their recommendations, which in general were that I should send up each section of ms as rapidly as completed. This would not prevent making further changes if necessary.

Went to the U.C. Library at 1:45; looked up a few things but had no luck. At 2:45 I went down to MVZ. Stebbins was doing some elaborate work on Xantusias vigilis so I spent the rest of the time with the card catalogue. Made a list of the Mexican rattlers accessioned since about 1960. There were a lot that looked good and I may send for them.

Met GG at 4 PM at Shattuck and University and went back to the hotel.

(Continued on Nov. 5)

*Asst Director

At the office this morning, a little tired from staying up so late last night.

Worked on bibliographic items. Decided to try to make a clean-up by asking for interlibrary loans on a lot of items that have been hanging free for a long time So I made a list of them and took them over to the proper department of the Public Library.

Meeting of the Planning Committee of the Natural History Society from 5 to 6:15. Met with H.A. Price of Economic Research Associates and one of his associates, Rosen Thor. Discussed our problems at some length. He will submit a proposition before our next board meeting for surveying our situation with respect to both scope and finances. This was Dr. Hollander's Committee.

Friday, November 19, 1965

Got up at 3 and worked on miscellaneous items until about 5.

At the office for a brief time this morning. Then to the Public Library for a meeting of the Special Gifts Committee followed by a meeting of the Commission. Total time 9:30 to 11.

Worked on straightening out the inserts for Chapter 3, which had become confused.

Joe Copp came in this afternoon with a Stanford friend who had spent over a year in Chiapas, Mexico, where he made a good herp collection but no Rattlers. The are scarce there.

John Sloan came in to get the available catalinensis to have x-rays taken of their tails.

David Jr. stayed tonight.

Saturday, November 20, 1965

Worked this morning at 2:30 on the inserts for Chapter 3. They require few changes.

Catch-up work today. Wrote a number of letters and cleaned up many details. I think I can say I'm now up to where I was when I went to San Francisco on Monday, Nov. 8. From now on I hope to get back and finish off that pestiferous section on Zoogeography. I still haven't heard from Mollath of the UC Press who promised to give his reaction to our conference and his recommendations for how to handle the manuscript in future.

Went to a dinner dance at the Fine Arts Gallery tonight; for me a noisy, unintelligible affair, during which I couldn't hear what anyone said or get anything out of it if I did. Home at 10:30.

Sunday, November 21, 1965

Had a very stultifying and unrewarding time today. I worked briefly on the AMNH specimens of oaxacus and nigrescens and then found I had apparently lost the Ms copy of Table 27; the most critical table of all. I finally located a superseded copy dated June 5, 1965, which may have all the latest changes and additions, but I cant be sure. I spent a lot of time searching high and low for the missing table but had no luck. I will make a copy of the superseded edition that I did find and hope that no further changes have been made in the lost copy. I must have thrown it away by mistake but still hope it will show up somewhere. A most disquieting episodes.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 03/13/2014 01:08 AM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:15 PM

Monday, November 22, 1965

This morning I got up at 4:30 and read through the diary beginning with June 7 when I last revised table 2:7. I found 2 places where I had certainly used it; once when I cheeked Pistoia's Repidus' body blotches, and Oct. 2 when I checked Sloan's counts and others he had made. So the next step is to look for the missing copy at the office.

I also observed how much my writing has deteriorated during the past year. But it did show the value of keeping the diary.

Made up a piece of the Mexican key to aid in checking the 4 AMNH specimens of oaxacus and nigrescens in the basement. Worked at these items until 7 AM.

At the office this morning. Saw Phil who had just returned from New York. Had a phone conversation with Don Clark about the recent meeting of the Natural History Museum's Planning Committee.

Worked on Zoogeography. Went to bank, Nelson Moors for slippers, and bookstore. Raining.

This noon to my intense relief and satisfaction I found the missing copy of Table 2.7. I had filed it in the lepidus envelope when I made an entry of the data secured from Pistoia. This will save a lot of work preparing a duplicate.

Took letters up to Miss Molloy.

Tuesday, November 23, 1965

At the office most of the morning. Continued work on Zoogeography. Went out shopping for rubber stripping for windows and doors. Not much luck. Also lamps.

At 10:50 Philip asked me to go up to Roosevelt School and pick up Janet, which I did and took her home. She had a slight fever.

In the afternoon I repaired an iron rest. Also went shopping for weather stripping. Went to 3 stores and got some stuff at one of them that may work.

Zoo meeting of Financial Committee and Trustees; with dinner; 5:30 to 8. A peaceful meeting.

Wednesday, November 24, 1965

Got up at 5 and cleaned up some miscellaneous items.

Went to Whiting Mead on the way to work. They had no rubber strips such as I wanted.

At the office briefly. Then to Dr. Sam Emery Dentist and was in the dentist chair from 10:30 to 11:30. Had two fillings that had fallen out replaced. On the way back to the office went to Woolworths, (blank), and SD Hardware and picked up another striping device. After lunch went to Sears and picked up another, but none was the rubber strip that I thought would work best. Ordered roses for tomorrow on the way to Sears.

When I got home started work on the troublesome library windows. Worked for at least 2 hours and fixed the east window. I think (and hope) it will be OK. Wore myself out on this.

A Mr. Hardman (one of the Spiegl tube) from Seattle phoned this afternoon He is disappointed in the rain and is leaving tomorrow. I wouldn't give him much of a welcome, being both tired out and tied up tonight and tomorrow. I tried to be cordial but didn't produce much under the circumstances.

Got nice congratulatory letters today from Howard Chernoff and Ray Cowles.

Tonight went to the final opera of the year, Fledermaus. Light stuff but I enjoyed it

Friday, December 31, 1965

Got up at 4:30 and made out sheets for the borrowed rattlers in the basement, MVZ pricei and others. Finished at 6:15.

Today I did some scale counting particularly MVZ specimens in the basement. But I didn't do very well. I had to spend a lot of time getting 2 kerosene heaters working as it was cold. This took a lot of time and tired me out. Mary Gould and Ellen came to lunch.

It was a poor day and I got very tired with little accomplished.

Looking over last year's work it has been extremely disappointing. At the beginning of the year I was working on the keys and tables in Chapter 2. They are now finished except for a few last minute changes. But I stymied on Zoogeography and the end of Chapter 3. I must be guided by the failures of 1965, or I will never get through. Here I am 82 years old and not able to work long hours on anything. I will have to use good sense in deciding on the extent of all changes to be instituted in Edition 2 or the entire project will be unfinished and no one else can finish it. Unnecessary modifications and biblio references will have to be cut to a minimum. Have I the judgment?

Chuck Wagon

Midway Chuck Wagon
Midway Drive at Rosecrans
San Diego 6, Calif.

Delicious choice of prime ribs -- all you can eat for $2.29 is the slogan of the Midway Chuck Wagon. Customers are invited to dine "Chuck Wagon Style" in a quaint Western atmosphere. Enjoy your favorite cocktails in the unique Gaslight Bar or the Longbranch Saloon where top names in the entertainment world will entertain you. The policy of giving the people what they want in quality... price... and service... has made the Midway Chuck Wagon the outstanding eating and entertainment attraction of the West.
